The "salary" column qualifies as personal data under GDPR Article 4(1) when linked to an identified or identifiable natural person (employee ID, name, email, or any combination of quasi-identifiers), so it falls within the regulation's full scope. It is not a "special category" under Article 9 (which covers health, race, religion, biometrics, sexual orientation, union membership, etc.), but salary is widely treated as sensitive personal/financial data warranting heightened protection under Article 5 principles (lawfulness, purpose limitation, data minimization, accuracy, storage limitation, integrity & confidentiality) and Article 32 (security of processing). Lawful basis is typically Article 6(1)(b) contract performance for payroll, 6(1)(c) legal obligation for tax/social security reporting, and sometimes 6(1)(f) legitimate interests for analytics — never consent in an employer/employee context due to the power imbalance (EDPB guidance). Data subject rights apply: access (Art. 15), rectification (Art. 16), erasure where lawful (Art. 17), portability (Art. 20), and restriction (Art. 18). Cross-border transfers require Chapter V safeguards (SCCs, adequacy decisions). Retention should be bounded by statutory payroll/tax record requirements (commonly 5–10 years depending on jurisdiction), then deleted or anonymized. A DPIA (Art. 35) may be required if salary is combined with profiling, performance scoring, or large-scale monitoring.

Under the CIA triad, classify as follows. Confidentiality: HIGH — unauthorized disclosure causes reputational, legal (GDPR fines up to 4% global turnover or €20M), contractual, and interpersonal harm (pay equity disputes, discrimination claims, social engineering, extortion). Apply strict role-based access control (least privilege, need-to-know limited to HR, payroll, finance, and the data subject), column-level access controls, attribute-based access where possible, encryption at rest (AES-256, ideally column-level or application-layer encryption / TDE), encryption in transit (TLS 1.2+), tokenization or format-preserving encryption for non-production environments, dynamic data masking for analysts, pseudonymization for reporting datasets, robust key management (HSM/KMS with rotation), and comprehensive audit logging of every read/write with tamper-evident storage. Integrity: HIGH — incorrect salary values cause direct financial loss, tax non-compliance, legal liability, and erode trust. Enforce schema constraints (NOT NULL, CHECK for non-negative and within plausible bounds, appropriate numeric/decimal type with fixed precision to avoid floating-point drift, currency code column alongside), referential integrity to employee table, application-level validation, four-eyes/maker-checker approval for changes, immutable audit/history tables (temporal tables or change data capture), cryptographic hashing or digital signatures for payroll batches, database triggers for change tracking, segregation of duties between requestor and approver, and reconciliation controls against source-of-truth HR systems. Availability: MEDIUM (often MEDIUM-HIGH around payroll cycles) — salary data must be available for monthly/biweekly payroll runs and statutory reporting deadlines, but brief outages outside those windows are tolerable. Mitigate via regular encrypted backups with tested restore procedures, defined RPO/RTO aligned to payroll calendar, high-availability database configuration (replication, failover), DR plan, and capacity planning.

Overall classification: Confidential / Restricted / Sensitive Personal Financial Data — highest-tier confidentiality, high integrity, medium availability, fully in-scope for GDPR with strict lawful basis, minimization, security, retention, and data-subject-rights obligations.
